            <ce:date-received day="15" month="6" year="2021"/>
            <ce:date-revised day="7" month="10" year="2021"/>
            <ce:date-accepted day="10" month="10" year="2021"/>
            
            <ce:abstract class="author" xml:lang="en" id="ab010" view="all"><ce:abstract-sec id="as010" view="all">
                  <ce:simple-para id="sp0010" view="all">Mediterranean forests are important sources of income for society and represent biodiversity hotspots, characterized by a mosaic of forest structures, from short-rotation even-aged stands to old-growth forests. However, such increased complexity requires forest management to balance timber production with biodiversity conservation at various spatial scales. This study investigated the impacts of forest structures and management alternatives on the occurrence and richness of Tree-related Microhabitats (TreMs) – as proxies for forest biodiversity – in three Mediterranean forests in Italy. The generalized linear mixed model was applied to assess the relationship between a large set of forest structural parameters and the occurrence and richness of TreMs at the tree level, and resulted in an overall model accuracy higher than 80%. The same model was then implemented in hypothetical forest structures, resulting from no management, close-to-nature forestry and combined management system. Results show that at early developmental stages of the stand, no management slightly anticipates the occurrence of TreMs, while in mature forests, the combined forest management system effectively balances forest productivity with biodiversity conservation. The close-to-nature management system is recommended for promoting TreMs richness. Such findings might be used to support sustainable forest management and valorise the multifunctional role of Mediterranean forests.</ce:simple-para>
               </ce:abstract-sec></ce:abstract>
            <ce:keywords class="keyword" xml:lang="en" id="kg005" view="all">
               <ce:section-title id="st015">Keywords</ce:section-title>
               <ce:keyword id="k0005">
                  <ce:text>Forest structure</ce:text>
               </ce:keyword>
               <ce:keyword id="k0010">
                  <ce:text>Forestry</ce:text>
               </ce:keyword>
               <ce:keyword id="k0015">
                  <ce:text>Forest biodiversity</ce:text>
               </ce:keyword>
               <ce:keyword id="k0020">
                  <ce:text>Naturalness</ce:text>
               </ce:keyword>
               <ce:keyword id="k0025">
                  <ce:text>Habitat tree</ce:text>
               </ce:keyword>
               <ce:keyword id="pc_ZHdt85ci4w">
                  <ce:text>Integrative</ce:text>
               </ce:keyword>
            </ce:keywords>
         </head>
         <body view="all">
            <ce:sections>
               <ce:section id="s0005" view="all">
                  <ce:label>1</ce:label>
                  <ce:section-title id="st020">Introduction</ce:section-title>
                  <ce:para id="p0030" view="all">Forests in EU cover about 37% of the total land and provide multiple benefits to society, ranging from biodiversity conservation to climate change mitigation and adaptation, soil protection and timber production. However, the biodiversity status of forests in EU has not improved over the last years (<ce:cross-ref refid="b0185" id="c0080">Maes et al., 2020</ce:cross-ref>). Moreover, functionality and resilience of EU forests are increasingly affected by climate change-related disturbances and other extreme events (e.g. <ce:cross-ref refid="b0245" id="c0085">Pilli et al., 2021</ce:cross-ref>). Sustainable forest management (SFM) may strengthen resilience and adaptation of habitat types towards ensuring the continuous flow of goods and services to people (<ce:cross-ref refid="b0300" id="c0090">Smith et al., 2020</ce:cross-ref>). The new EU forest strategy also stresses on the need for the conservation of biodiversity through modern, climate neutral and a resource-efficient forest management (<ce:cross-ref refid="b0095" id="c0095">European Commission, 2021</ce:cross-ref>). To this aim, some promising forest strategies have been discussed so far, such as e.g. forest landscape restoration (<ce:cross-ref refid="b0080" id="c0100">Crouzeilles et al., 2020</ce:cross-ref>), diversification of forest plantations (<ce:cross-ref refid="b0210" id="c0105">Messier et al., 2021</ce:cross-ref>), and preservation of primary and old-growth forests (<ce:cross-ref refid="b0035" id="c0110">Barredo Cano et al., 2021</ce:cross-ref>). Nonetheless, the fragmentation of forest ownership, the variety of climate and vegetation patterns, and the differences in forest management systems in Europe may hinder an effective implementation of such strategies.</ce:para>
                  <ce:para id="p0035" view="all">Since early 90′s, Europe’s forests have been managed according to the SFM principles and goals. The conservation of forest biodiversity has become one of the main forest management goals (see also <ce:cross-ref refid="b0095" id="c0115">European Commission, 2021</ce:cross-ref>). However, balancing the trade-offs between biodiversity conservation and services such as e.g. timber production, is a difficult task (<ce:cross-refs refid="b0070 b0190" id="r0030">Cosyns et al., 2020; Maier and Winkel, 2017</ce:cross-refs>). On the one hand, managing forests mainly for timber production and climate regulation can simultaneously provide income for forest owners and ensure mitigation though increasing net GHG removals and valorising a smarter use of harvested wood products, including their substitution effects (e.g. climate-smart forestry; (<ce:cross-refs refid="b0275 b0325" id="r0035">Santopuoli et al., 2020; Verkerk et al., 2020</ce:cross-refs>)). On the other hand, an effective conservation of biodiversity often requires the retention of large trees bearing habitats for numerous living organisms (<ce:cross-refs refid="b0120 b0310" id="r0040">Gustafsson et al., 2020; Storch et al., 2020</ce:cross-refs>), to the detriment of timber production.</ce:para>
                  <ce:para id="p0040" view="all">Balancing nature conservation and economic management represents the core issue within the recent integrative forest management approach (<ce:cross-ref refid="b0150" id="c0120">Kraus and Krumm, 2013</ce:cross-ref>). The integrative approach was developed as an alternative to the segregative approach to strengthen the combination between nature conservation and timber production. In the last years, Tree-related microhabitats (TreMs) have been seen as a tool to support the integrative approach (<ce:cross-ref refid="b0065" id="c0125">Bütler et al., 2013</ce:cross-ref>), recognizing that their occurrence and richness are of vital importance for several living organisms (<ce:cross-ref refid="b0175" id="c0130">Larrieu et al., 2018</ce:cross-ref>), and thus very useful for assessing forest biodiversity (<ce:cross-ref refid="b9000" id="c9213">Oettel and Lapin, 2021</ce:cross-ref>).</ce:para>
                  <ce:para id="p0045" view="all">According to <ce:cross-ref refid="b0145" id="c0135">Kraus et al. (2016)</ce:cross-ref> there are 64 types of TreMs; recently organized in a hierarchical typology by <ce:cross-ref refid="b0175" id="c0140">Larrieu et al. (2018)</ce:cross-ref> including “Form”; “Group” and “Type”. Their occurrence and frequency are strictly linked to the forest naturalness and aging of trees (<ce:cross-refs refid="b0140 b0235 b0225" id="r0045">Kozák et al., 2018; Paillet et al., 2019; 2017</ce:cross-refs>). They also represent useful proxies to assess the degree of naturalness of old-growth forests and forests with no recent harvesting activities (<ce:cross-ref refid="b0270" id="c0145">Santopuoli et al., 2019</ce:cross-ref>). Considering their occurrence on living trees, TreMs might be used as indicators for biodiversity (<ce:cross-refs refid="b0040 b0230" id="r0050">Basile et al., 2020; Paillet et al., 2018</ce:cross-refs>) or naturalness in ordinarily managed stands (<ce:cross-ref refid="b0010" id="c0150">Asbeck et al., 2021</ce:cross-ref>). The presence of large trees is more frequently used to predict TreMs abundance (<ce:cross-ref refid="b0225" id="c0155">Paillet et al., 2017</ce:cross-ref>), additional aspects influencing TreMs have been explored, such as e.g. forest ownership (<ce:cross-refs refid="b0130 b0260" id="r0055">Johann and Schaich, 2016; Regnery et al., 2013</ce:cross-refs>), management objectives (<ce:cross-refs refid="b0165 b0330" id="r0060">Larrieu et al., 2012; Vuidot et al., 2011</ce:cross-refs>) and degree of naturalness (<ce:cross-ref refid="b0340" id="c0160">Winter and Möller, 2008</ce:cross-ref>). TreMs-related studies in Europe are mounting but mostly focus on temperate forests (e.g., <ce:cross-refs refid="b0160 b0110 b0020" id="r0065">Larrieu and Cabanettes, 2012; Großmann et al., 2018; Asbeck et al., 2019</ce:cross-refs>). There is indeed limited knowledge on TreMs in the Mediterranean forests (<ce:cross-refs refid="b0175 b0200 b0270" id="r0070">Larrieu et al., 2018; Marziliano et al.; 2021; Santopuoli et al., 2019</ce:cross-refs>). In Mediterranean region, the progressive abandonment of management practices, the fragmentation of forest ownership, as well as the presence of peculiar characteristics of forest stands (e.g. species mixture) could have contributed so far to forest aging processes with subsequent increase in occurrence and richness of TreMs (<ce:cross-ref refid="b0320" id="c0165">Vacchiano et al., 2017</ce:cross-ref>). Assessing the relationships between TreMs and forest structural parameters in Mediterranean forests has become relevant to predict the occurrence and richness of TreMs and to understand the dynamics of TreMs development, as well as the impacts on the other taxa, as already highlighted in literature. For example, <ce:cross-ref refid="b0020" id="c0170">Asbeck et al. (2019)</ce:cross-ref> demonstrated that TreMs abundance increases with tree size; particularly with diameter, while the tree species mixture affects the diversity of TreMs. <ce:cross-ref refid="b0110" id="c0175">Großmann et al. (2018)</ce:cross-ref> highlighted that smaller trees can bear specific TreMs; and thus playing an important ecological role in conventionally managed forests. However, there are still knowledge gaps on how other forest structural parameters, such as e.g. tree height, crown projection area and slenderness coefficient influence TreMs occurrence and richness.</ce:para>
                  <ce:para id="p0050" view="all">To fill these gaps, the present study aims to assess the occurrence and richness of TreMs on more than 1400 trees from Central and Southern Italy, including their relationships with relevant forest structural parameters. In particular, we seek to address the following questions: (i) does tree species composition affect the occurrence and richness of TreMs?; (ii) what are the forest structural parameters with the largest impact on the occurrence and richness of TreMs?. In addition, we predict the impact of two hypothetical forest management strategies on the occurrence and richness of TreMs.</ce:para>
               </ce:section>
               <ce:section id="s0010" view="all">
                  <ce:label>2</ce:label>
                  <ce:section-title id="st025">Material and methods</ce:section-title>
                  <ce:section id="s0015" view="all">
                     <ce:label>2.1</ce:label>
                     <ce:section-title id="st030">Study area</ce:section-title>
                     <ce:para id="p0055" view="all">This study was carried out through inventorying 1416 trees distributed in three one-hectare forest plots (100x100 m), located in central-southern Apennines, Italy (<ce:cross-ref refid="f0005" id="c0180">Fig. 1</ce:cross-ref>
                        <ce:float-anchor refid="f0005"/>): Campaegli (Lazio region), Bosco Pennataro (Molise region) and Giffone (Calabria region). The study areas differ for tree species composition, ownership regime and main forest function. Campaegli and Giffone are two pure beech forests (<ce:italic>Fagus sylvatica</ce:italic> L.), which are regularly managed mostly for timber production. Campaegli belongs to the “<ce:italic>Monti Simbruini Regional Park</ce:italic>”, an important site for balancing nature conservation and socio-economic aspects (<ce:cross-ref refid="b0285" id="c0185">Sillo et al., 2012</ce:cross-ref>). Giffone is close to the Aspromonte National Park and has also important nature-related values. The economic and ecological concerns play a major role in these forests, and for this reason, the current forest management approach refers to combined objective forestry (<ce:cross-ref refid="b0085" id="c0190">Duncker et al., 2012</ce:cross-ref>).</ce:para>
                     <ce:para id="p0060" view="all">Bosco Pennataro is a multi-layered, mixed forest composed by oak (<ce:italic>Quercus cerris</ce:italic> L.), beech (<ce:italic>Fagus sylvatica</ce:italic> L.) and other broadleaved species. This site falls within the Natura 2000 network and the “<ce:italic>Collemeluccio-Montedimezzo Alto Molise</ce:italic>” UNESCO Man and Biosphere Reserve. The primary management goal is biodiversity conservation characterized by a continuous forest cover and lack of forest interventions from decades. According to <ce:cross-ref refid="b0085" id="c0195">Duncker et al. (2012)</ce:cross-ref>, the forest management approach of this forest can be classified as passive (i.e., unmanaged).</ce:para>
                  </ce:section>
                  <ce:section id="s0020" view="all">
                     <ce:label>2.2</ce:label>
                     <ce:section-title id="st035">Field data</ce:section-title>
                     <ce:para id="p0065" view="all">The field surveys’ campaign was realized between 2016 and 2017, using the Field-Map technology, and concerned the mapping of all living trees with diameter at breast height (DBH) ≥ 10 cm. For each tree, tree species and several quantitative parameters (e.g., DBH, tree height (H), crown projection area (CPA), and crown base (CB)) were collected and used in this study (<ce:cross-ref refid="t0005" id="c0200">Table 1</ce:cross-ref>
                        <ce:float-anchor refid="t0005"/>). Other tree structural parameters, such as crown length (CL = H - CB), live-to-crown ratio (LCR = CL H<ce:sup loc="post">−1</ce:sup>), slenderness coefficient (SL = H DBH<ce:sup loc="post">−1</ce:sup>), basal area (BA, m<ce:sup loc="post">2</ce:sup>) and the volume (V, m<ce:sup loc="post">3</ce:sup>) were calculated and additionally used in this study (<ce:cross-ref refid="t0010" id="c0205">Table 2</ce:cross-ref>
                        <ce:float-anchor refid="t0010"/>). The volume of each tree was calculated based on growth equations from <ce:cross-ref refid="b0315" id="c0210">Tabacchi et al. (2011)</ce:cross-ref>.</ce:para>
                     <ce:para id="p0070" view="all">A total of 1416 living trees were inventoried and used in the analysis. Standing dead trees were not considered in this study. About two-thirds of the inventoried trees bearing TreMs (<ce:cross-ref refid="t0010" id="c0215">Table 2</ce:cross-ref>) for a total of 911 TreM-trees. The ratio between TreM-trees and total number of trees is higher in Campeagli (74%) and Giffone (67%), than in Pennataro (54%). The lower value in Pennataro is justified by the uneven-aged structure characterized by a higher frequency of smaller trees (see Annex 1 in supplementary material). Trees in Pennataro are characterized by a more heterogeneous DBH distribution with the lowest median value and the highest DBH in absolute terms among all sites. In Campaegli, the DBH range is smaller, even if the number of trees is the highest. The DBH distribution in Giffone is regular with the highest median value.</ce:para>
                     <ce:para id="p0075" view="all">We inventoried TreMs using the TreMs Reference Field List (<ce:cross-ref refid="b0145" id="c0220">Kraus et al., 2016</ce:cross-ref>) recently arranged as TreMs hierarchical typology (<ce:cross-ref refid="b0175" id="c0225">Larrieu et al., 2018</ce:cross-ref>). In particular, we observed the occurrence (presence/absence) and richness (TreMs of different type) of TreMs on each tree. Excluding the least frequent TreMs types (frequency &lt; 20), 16 out of 64 TreMs types resulted as the most recurrent in this study, particularly belonging to the <ce:italic>Forms</ce:italic>: <ce:italic>Cavities</ce:italic> (<ce:italic>trunk rot hole</ce:italic>, <ce:italic>hollow branch</ce:italic>, <ce:italic>dendrotelm</ce:italic> and <ce:italic>root buttress concavity</ce:italic>), <ce:italic>Crown deadwood</ce:italic> (<ce:italic>dead branches</ce:italic>), <ce:italic>Epiphytic and parasitic structures</ce:italic> (<ce:italic>bryophytes</ce:italic>, <ce:italic>lianas</ce:italic>, <ce:italic>crown microsoil</ce:italic>) and <ce:italic>Fresh exudates</ce:italic> (<ce:italic>sap run</ce:italic>) (see Annex 2 in the supplementary material). Based on the observation of the current state, we assessed the relationships between tree parameters and TreMs occurrence and richness with the main purpose to understand the role of structural parameters for each individual tree.</ce:para>
                  </ce:section>
                  <ce:section id="s0025" view="all">
                     <ce:label>2.3</ce:label>
                     <ce:section-title id="st040">Predicting tree-related microhabitats occurrence and richness</ce:section-title>
                     <ce:para id="p0080" view="all">We performed statistical analyses with R software version 4.0.3 (<ce:cross-ref refid="b0255" id="c0230">R Core Team, 2013</ce:cross-ref>). After assessing multicollinearity between structural parameters using <ce:italic>vifstep</ce:italic> (<ce:italic>usdm</ce:italic> R package (<ce:cross-ref refid="b0215" id="c0235">Naimi, 2017</ce:cross-ref>)) (threshold = 0.7), we proceeded with the analysis throughout three subsequent steps. Firstly, starting with non-multicollinear parameters, we ran several models for occurrence and richness, replacing each time the parameters with those highly correlated (≥0.7). Secondly, we ran the Generalized Linear Model (GLM) and selected the best set of variables for each model using the “backward” selection (<ce:italic>stats</ce:italic> R package). We selected the Binomial error family to predict occurrence (presence/absence), and the Poisson error family to predict richness (from 0 to 11 types of TreMs). We compared these models with Akaike’s Information Criterion (AIC) and selected the model with the lowest AIC, for both occurrence and richness (<ce:cross-ref refid="t0015" id="c0240">Table 3</ce:cross-ref>
                        <ce:float-anchor refid="t0015"/>). Residual diagnostics, as well as over-dispersion and zero-inflation tests were completed using DHARMa R package (<ce:cross-ref id="opt4PKFUeWULy" refid="bib342">Hartig, 2017</ce:cross-ref>). See Annex 3 in the supplementary material for further details about the correlation matrix among forest structural parameters and the over-dispersion output.</ce:para>
                     <ce:para id="p0085" view="all">We used tree species as a random effect. Our reasoning was that tree species differ in the quantity and quality of TreMs provided at tree level (<ce:cross-ref refid="b0020" id="c0245">Asbeck et al., 2019</ce:cross-ref>) and that the occurrence of TreMs can be explained by tree species functional group (<ce:cross-ref refid="b0005" id="c0250">Asbeck et al., 2020a</ce:cross-ref>). For the best GLM occurrence and richness models, we ran the Generalized Linear Mixed Model (GLMM) using <ce:italic>lme4</ce:italic> R package (<ce:cross-ref refid="b0045" id="c0255">Bates et al., 2015</ce:cross-ref>) to assess whether or not tree species variability could have an impact on the model-fits. More precisely, we considered the forest species as a random variable because its levels (11 species) are conceived as a subset of the possible groups that could be sampled from a larger population. The <ce:italic>performance</ce:italic> R package (<ce:cross-ref refid="b0180" id="c0260">Lüdecke et al., 2020</ce:cross-ref>) was used to evaluate the accuracy of the occurrence model according to the Area Under Curve (AUC), while the <ce:italic>pROC</ce:italic> R package (<ce:cross-ref refid="b0265" id="c0265">Robin et al., 2011</ce:cross-ref>) was used to calculate the AUC of the Receiver Operating Characteristic Curve (ROC) of richness model. Once the models improved, we selected those performing better (<ce:cross-ref refid="t0020" id="c0270">Table 4</ce:cross-ref>
                        <ce:float-anchor refid="t0020"/>).</ce:para>
                  </ce:section>
                  <ce:section id="s0030" view="all">
                     <ce:label>2.4</ce:label>
                     <ce:section-title id="st045">Sensitivity analysis by management system</ce:section-title>
                     <ce:para id="p0090" view="all">We tested how structural parameters would change if a different management system was implemented under current conditions. Starting from current structural conditions in our sites, we created hypothetical structural parameters based on their relative variation when passing from unmanaged to managed stands, either with close-to-nature and combined management systems, and <ce:italic>vice versa</ce:italic> (see <ce:cross-ref id="opt5CCbmWGet0" refid="t0025">Table 5</ce:cross-ref>
                        <ce:float-anchor refid="t0025"/>).</ce:para>
                     <ce:para id="p0095" view="all">Close to nature forestry has the main objective of emulating the impact of natural processes and promoting natural regeneration of native or site-adapted species (see e.g. <ce:cross-ref refid="b0085" id="c0285">Duncker et al., 2012</ce:cross-ref>). Close to nature forestry also seeks to enhance the vertical and horizontal structures’ diversification, often through single tree or group selection practices, or shelterwood systems (i.e. clearcuts avoided; <ce:cross-ref refid="b0060" id="c0290">Brang et al., 2014</ce:cross-ref>). On the other hand, combined objective forestry helps ensuring multiple objectives beyond timber production, such as for example, habitat preservation and soil protection, availability of non-wood products, recreation, mainly through less intensive practices compared to an even-aged forest management system (see e.g. <ce:cross-ref refid="b0085" id="c0295">Duncker et al., 2012</ce:cross-ref>). The management principles of close to nature and combined objective forestry might overlap if other forest management variables are considered beyond harvest intensity <ce:italic>per se</ce:italic> (e.g. environmental gradients, <ce:cross-ref refid="b0060" id="c0300">Brang et al., 2014</ce:cross-ref>) or forest management needs to incorporate complexity and adaptability of forest ecosystems, especially in Europe (see e.g. <ce:cross-ref refid="b0050" id="c0305">Bauhus et al., 2013</ce:cross-ref>). However, we use here “close to nature” and “combined objective” management <ce:italic>sensu</ce:italic> (<ce:cross-ref refid="b0085" id="c0310">Duncker et al., 2012</ce:cross-ref>) as overarching management strategies to qualitatively represent the theoretical impact of human interventions on structural parameters under investigation.</ce:para>
                     <ce:para id="p0100" view="all">In case of Pennataro, we calculated the hypothetical structural parameter <mml:math altimg="si6.svg">
                           <mml:mi>i</mml:mi>
                        </mml:math> in both close-to-nature management and combined management with equations <ce:cross-refs refid="e0005 e0010" id="r9000">[1-2]</ce:cross-refs>.<ce:display>
                           <ce:formula id="e0005">
                              <ce:label>(1)</ce:label>
                              <mml:math altimg="si7.svg">
                                 <mml:mrow>
                                    <mml:msub>
                                       <mml:mrow>
                                          <mml:mi mathvariant="italic">PAR</mml:mi>
                                       </mml:mrow>
                                       <mml:mrow>
                                          <mml:mi mathvariant="italic">ctn</mml:mi>
                                       </mml:mrow>
                                    </mml:msub>
                                    <mml:mo linebreak="goodbreak">=</mml:mo>
                                    <mml:msub>
                                       <mml:mrow>
                                          <mml:mi mathvariant="italic">PAR</mml:mi>
                                       </mml:mrow>
                                       <mml:mrow>
                                          <mml:mi mathvariant="italic">un</mml:mi>
                                       </mml:mrow>
                                    </mml:msub>
                                    <mml:mo>∙</mml:mo>
                                    <mml:mfenced open="(" close=")">
                                       <mml:mrow>
                                          <mml:mn>1</mml:mn>
                                          <mml:mo linebreak="badbreak">+</mml:mo>
                                          <mml:msub>
                                             <mml:mrow>
                                                <mml:mi mathvariant="italic">dPAR</mml:mi>
                                             </mml:mrow>
                                             <mml:mrow>
                                                <mml:mi mathvariant="italic">un</mml:mi>
                                                <mml:mo stretchy="false">→</mml:mo>
                                                <mml:mi>c</mml:mi>
                                                <mml:mi>t</mml:mi>
                                                <mml:mi>n</mml:mi>
                                             </mml:mrow>
                                          </mml:msub>
                                       </mml:mrow>
                                    </mml:mfenced>
                                    <mml:mrow>
                                       <mml:mo stretchy="false">(</mml:mo>
                                       <mml:mi>i</mml:mi>
                                       <mml:mo>=</mml:mo>
                                       <mml:mn>1</mml:mn>
                                       <mml:mo>,</mml:mo>
                                       <mml:mo>⋯</mml:mo>
                                       <mml:mo>,</mml:mo>
                                       <mml:mi>n</mml:mi>
                                       <mml:mo stretchy="false">)</mml:mo>
                                    </mml:mrow>
                                 </mml:mrow>
                              </mml:math>
                           </ce:formula>
                        </ce:display>
                        <ce:display>
                           <ce:formula id="e0010">
                              <ce:label>(2)</ce:label>
                              <mml:math altimg="si8.svg">
                                 <mml:mrow>
                                    <mml:msub>
                                       <mml:mrow>
                                          <mml:mi mathvariant="italic">PAR</mml:mi>
                                       </mml:mrow>
                                       <mml:mrow>
                                          <mml:mi mathvariant="italic">co</mml:mi>
                                       </mml:mrow>
                                    </mml:msub>
                                    <mml:mo linebreak="goodbreak">=</mml:mo>
                                    <mml:msub>
                                       <mml:mrow>
                                          <mml:mi mathvariant="italic">PAR</mml:mi>
                                       </mml:mrow>
                                       <mml:mrow>
                                          <mml:mi mathvariant="italic">un</mml:mi>
                                       </mml:mrow>
                                    </mml:msub>
                                    <mml:mo>∙</mml:mo>
                                    <mml:mfenced open="(" close=")">
                                       <mml:mrow>
                                          <mml:mn>1</mml:mn>
                                          <mml:mo linebreak="badbreak">+</mml:mo>
                                          <mml:msub>
                                             <mml:mrow>
                                                <mml:mi mathvariant="italic">dPAR</mml:mi>
                                             </mml:mrow>
                                             <mml:mrow>
                                                <mml:mi mathvariant="italic">un</mml:mi>
                                                <mml:mo stretchy="false">→</mml:mo>
                                                <mml:mi>c</mml:mi>
                                                <mml:mi>o</mml:mi>
                                             </mml:mrow>
                                          </mml:msub>
                                       </mml:mrow>
                                    </mml:mfenced>
                                    <mml:mrow>
                                       <mml:mo stretchy="false">(</mml:mo>
                                       <mml:mi>i</mml:mi>
                                       <mml:mo>=</mml:mo>
                                       <mml:mn>1</mml:mn>
                                       <mml:mo>,</mml:mo>
                                       <mml:mo>⋯</mml:mo>
                                       <mml:mo>,</mml:mo>
                                       <mml:mi>n</mml:mi>
                                       <mml:mo stretchy="false">)</mml:mo>
                                    </mml:mrow>
                                 </mml:mrow>
                              </mml:math>
                           </ce:formula>
                        </ce:display>where: <mml:math altimg="si9.svg">
                           <mml:msub>
                              <mml:mrow>
                                 <mml:mi mathvariant="italic">PAR</mml:mi>
                              </mml:mrow>
                              <mml:mrow>
                                 <mml:mi mathvariant="italic">ctn</mml:mi>
                              </mml:mrow>
                           </mml:msub>
                        </mml:math> is the value of a given structural parameter in stands with close-to-nature management; <mml:math altimg="si10.svg">
                           <mml:msub>
                              <mml:mrow>
                                 <mml:mi mathvariant="italic">PAR</mml:mi>
                              </mml:mrow>
                              <mml:mrow>
                                 <mml:mi mathvariant="italic">un</mml:mi>
                              </mml:mrow>
                           </mml:msub>
                        </mml:math> is the value of a given structural parameter in unmanaged stands; <mml:math altimg="si11.svg">
                           <mml:msub>
                              <mml:mrow>
                                 <mml:mi mathvariant="italic">dPAR</mml:mi>
                              </mml:mrow>
                              <mml:mrow>
                                 <mml:mi mathvariant="italic">un</mml:mi>
                                 <mml:mo stretchy="false">→</mml:mo>
                                 <mml:mi>c</mml:mi>
                                 <mml:mi>t</mml:mi>
                                 <mml:mi>n</mml:mi>
                              </mml:mrow>
                           </mml:msub>
                        </mml:math> is the percentage variation of a given structural parameter when passing from unmanaged stands to stands with close-to-nature management (see <ce:cross-ref id="opt14GyTj5cW7" refid="t0025">Table 5</ce:cross-ref>); <mml:math altimg="si12.svg">
                           <mml:msub>
                              <mml:mrow>
                                 <mml:mi mathvariant="italic">PAR</mml:mi>
                              </mml:mrow>
                              <mml:mrow>
                                 <mml:mi mathvariant="italic">co</mml:mi>
                              </mml:mrow>
                           </mml:msub>
                        </mml:math> is the value of a given structural parameter in stands with combined management; <mml:math altimg="si13.svg">
                           <mml:msub>
                              <mml:mrow>
                                 <mml:mi mathvariant="italic">dPAR</mml:mi>
                              </mml:mrow>
                              <mml:mrow>
                                 <mml:mi mathvariant="italic">un</mml:mi>
                                 <mml:mo stretchy="false">→</mml:mo>
                                 <mml:mi>c</mml:mi>
                                 <mml:mi>o</mml:mi>
                              </mml:mrow>
                           </mml:msub>
                        </mml:math> is the percentage variation of a given structural parameter when passing from unmanaged stands to stands with combined management (see <ce:cross-ref id="optnOCu8GKZRL" refid="t0025">Table 5</ce:cross-ref>).</ce:para>
                     <ce:para id="p0105" view="all">Since <mml:math altimg="si14.svg">
                           <mml:mrow>
                              <mml:mi mathvariant="italic">dPAR</mml:mi>
                           </mml:mrow>
                        </mml:math> explains the structural differences when passing from no management to management conditions (i.e. one-way direction) (<ce:cross-ref id="optAKVbwOKRqd" refid="t0025">Table 5</ce:cross-ref>), for Campaegli and Giffone we calculated at first the hypothetical structural parameter <mml:math altimg="si6.svg">
                           <mml:mi>i</mml:mi>
                        </mml:math> in unmanaged stands (see equation <ce:cross-ref refid="e0015" id="c9005">[3]</ce:cross-ref>), and then we applied the <mml:math altimg="si14.svg">
                           <mml:mrow>
                              <mml:mi mathvariant="italic">dPAR</mml:mi>
                           </mml:mrow>
                        </mml:math> values as in <ce:cross-ref id="opt8OJcPoQxj2" refid="t0025">Table 5</ce:cross-ref> to obtain the hypothetical structural parameter <mml:math altimg="si6.svg">
                           <mml:mi>i</mml:mi>
                        </mml:math> in stands with close-to-nature management (see equation <ce:cross-ref refid="e0020" id="c9006">[4]</ce:cross-ref>).<ce:display>
                           <ce:formula id="e0015">
                              <ce:label>(3)</ce:label>
                              <mml:math altimg="si15.svg">
                                 <mml:mrow>
                                    <mml:msub>
                                       <mml:mrow>
                                          <mml:mi mathvariant="italic">PAR</mml:mi>
                                       </mml:mrow>
                                       <mml:mrow>
                                          <mml:mi mathvariant="italic">un</mml:mi>
                                       </mml:mrow>
                                    </mml:msub>
                                    <mml:mo linebreak="goodbreak">=</mml:mo>
                                    <mml:mfrac>
                                       <mml:msub>
                                          <mml:mrow>
                                             <mml:mi mathvariant="italic">PAR</mml:mi>
                                          </mml:mrow>
                                          <mml:mrow>
                                             <mml:mi mathvariant="italic">co</mml:mi>
                                          </mml:mrow>
                                       </mml:msub>
                                       <mml:mrow>
                                          <mml:mo stretchy="false">(</mml:mo>
                                          <mml:mn>1</mml:mn>
