                                 <mml:mi>o</mml:mi>
                              </mml:mrow>
                           </mml:msub>
                        </mml:math> is the percentage variation of a given structural parameter when passing from unmanaged stands to stands with combined management (see <ce:cross-ref id="optu7oMamyJ3m" refid="t0025">Table 5</ce:cross-ref>).<ce:display>
                           <ce:formula id="e0020">
                              <ce:label>(4)</ce:label>
                              <mml:math altimg="si7.svg">
                                 <mml:mrow>
                                    <mml:msub>
                                       <mml:mrow>
                                          <mml:mi mathvariant="italic">PAR</mml:mi>
                                       </mml:mrow>
                                       <mml:mrow>
                                          <mml:mi mathvariant="italic">ctn</mml:mi>
                                       </mml:mrow>
                                    </mml:msub>
                                    <mml:mo linebreak="goodbreak">=</mml:mo>
                                    <mml:msub>
                                       <mml:mrow>
                                          <mml:mi mathvariant="italic">PAR</mml:mi>
                                       </mml:mrow>
                                       <mml:mrow>
                                          <mml:mi mathvariant="italic">un</mml:mi>
                                       </mml:mrow>
                                    </mml:msub>
                                    <mml:mo>∙</mml:mo>
                                    <mml:mfenced open="(" close=")">
                                       <mml:mrow>
                                          <mml:mn>1</mml:mn>
                                          <mml:mo linebreak="badbreak">+</mml:mo>
                                          <mml:msub>
                                             <mml:mrow>
                                                <mml:mi mathvariant="italic">dPAR</mml:mi>
                                             </mml:mrow>
                                             <mml:mrow>
                                                <mml:mi mathvariant="italic">un</mml:mi>
                                                <mml:mo stretchy="false">→</mml:mo>
                                                <mml:mi>c</mml:mi>
                                                <mml:mi>t</mml:mi>
                                                <mml:mi>n</mml:mi>
                                             </mml:mrow>
                                          </mml:msub>
                                       </mml:mrow>
                                    </mml:mfenced>
                                    <mml:mrow>
                                       <mml:mo stretchy="false">(</mml:mo>
                                       <mml:mi>i</mml:mi>
                                       <mml:mo>=</mml:mo>
                                       <mml:mn>1</mml:mn>
                                       <mml:mo>,</mml:mo>
                                       <mml:mo>⋯</mml:mo>
                                       <mml:mo>,</mml:mo>
                                       <mml:mi>n</mml:mi>
                                       <mml:mo stretchy="false">)</mml:mo>
                                    </mml:mrow>
                                 </mml:mrow>
                              </mml:math>
                           </ce:formula>
                        </ce:display>where: <mml:math altimg="si9.svg">
                           <mml:msub>
                              <mml:mrow>
                                 <mml:mi mathvariant="italic">PAR</mml:mi>
                              </mml:mrow>
                              <mml:mrow>
                                 <mml:mi mathvariant="italic">ctn</mml:mi>
                              </mml:mrow>
                           </mml:msub>
                        </mml:math> is the value of a given structural parameter in stands with close-to-nature management; <mml:math altimg="si10.svg">
                           <mml:msub>
                              <mml:mrow>
                                 <mml:mi mathvariant="italic">PAR</mml:mi>
                              </mml:mrow>
                              <mml:mrow>
                                 <mml:mi mathvariant="italic">un</mml:mi>
                              </mml:mrow>
                           </mml:msub>
                        </mml:math> is the value of a given structural parameter in stands with combined management (calculated in equation <ce:cross-ref refid="e0015" id="c9007">[3]</ce:cross-ref>; <mml:math altimg="si11.svg">
                           <mml:msub>
                              <mml:mrow>
                                 <mml:mi mathvariant="italic">dPAR</mml:mi>
                              </mml:mrow>
                              <mml:mrow>
                                 <mml:mi mathvariant="italic">un</mml:mi>
                                 <mml:mo stretchy="false">→</mml:mo>
                                 <mml:mi>c</mml:mi>
                                 <mml:mi>t</mml:mi>
                                 <mml:mi>n</mml:mi>
                              </mml:mrow>
                           </mml:msub>
                        </mml:math> is the percentage variation of a given structural parameter when passing from unmanaged stands to stands with close-to-nature management (see <ce:cross-ref id="optEYiunNytoZ" refid="t0025">Table 5</ce:cross-ref>).</ce:para>
                     <ce:para id="p0110" view="all">This way, we obtained a new value for all considered structural parameters (see <ce:cross-ref id="optdaPrXpavat" refid="t0025">Table 5</ce:cross-ref>) in each of the six hypothetical stands, i.e. three stands ‘times’ two alternative management systems (excluding the current one). Through using the new value, we implemented the predict function of <ce:italic>lme4</ce:italic> R package (<ce:cross-ref refid="b0045" id="c0365">Bates et al., 2015</ce:cross-ref>) to predict the values of occurrence and richness of TreMs for each tree in all nine stands, i.e. three current stands ‘plus’ six hypothetical stands.</ce:para>
                  </ce:section>
               </ce:section>
               <ce:section id="s0035" view="all">
                  <ce:label>3</ce:label>
                  <ce:section-title id="st050">Results</ce:section-title>
                  <ce:section id="s0040" view="all">
                     <ce:label>3.1</ce:label>
                     <ce:section-title id="st055">Structural parameters and TreMs occurrence and richness</ce:section-title>
                     <ce:para id="p0115" view="all">The most impacting structural parameters are the DBH, and SL (p &lt; 0.001) for TreMs occurrence, while BA, H, V, SL (p &lt; 0.001) and LCR (p &lt; 0.05) show a significant impact on TreMs richness (<ce:cross-ref refid="t0030" id="c0370">Table 6</ce:cross-ref>
                        <ce:float-anchor refid="t0030"/>). More in detail, we found a direct positive relationship between the occurrence of TreMs and DBH, i.e. the occurrence of TreMs increases with an increase of DBH (coefficient = 1.38). On the contrary, we found a negative relationship between the occurrence of TreMs and SL (coefficient = −0.41), i.e. the occurrence of TreMs decreases with higher values of SL. Despite CPA was selected as an important variable, it plays a marginal role (coefficient = −0.23) for TreMs occurrence.</ce:para>
                     <ce:para id="p0120" view="all">The richness of TreMs increases with an increase in BA (coefficient = 0.49) and H (coefficient = 0.44), while it slightly increases with an increase of LCR (coefficient 0.05). On the contrary, a decrease in SL (coefficient −0.55) and V (coefficient −0.52) correspond to an increase of TreMs richness (see <ce:cross-ref refid="t0030" id="c0375">Table 6</ce:cross-ref>).</ce:para>
                     <ce:para id="p0125" view="all">Results confirm that the tree species composition plays an effect on both occurrence and richness of TreMs, as it improves the quality of results. We indeed obtained an accuracy of 81% (AIC = 1401, Pseudo-R<ce:sup loc="post">2</ce:sup> = 0.46; AUC = 81.3%) and of 87% (AIC = 3511; Pseudo R<ce:sup loc="post">2</ce:sup> = 0.52; AUC = 86.6%) for occurrence and richness respectively.</ce:para>
                  </ce:section>
                  <ce:section id="s0045" view="all">
                     <ce:label>3.2</ce:label>
                     <ce:section-title id="st060">Forest management systems and TreMs occurrence and richness</ce:section-title>
                     <ce:para id="p0130" view="all">In general, we found that DBH is the most impacting forest structural parameter for TreMs occurrence, which progressively increases with further increase in DBH (<ce:cross-ref refid="f0010" id="c0380">Fig. 2</ce:cross-ref>
                        <ce:float-anchor refid="f0010"/>). Despite the overall trend, the slope of curves is steeper for smaller diameters, particularly in Pennataro (higher variation of DBH, see Annex 1 in supplementary material), where we found an increase of 200% when moving from 15 cm to 25 cm DBH classes, compared to Campaegli and Giffone, for which the increment was of 100%. The occurrence of TreMs increases of about 235% moving from 15 cm to 45 cm DBH classes.</ce:para>
                     <ce:para id="p0135" view="all">The sensitivity analysis highlighted that alternative management systems could affect the occurrence of TreMs with a different impact depending on the forest structure (e.g., DBH, H, SL). In our study, the TreMs occurrence was slightly higher for no management than for close-to-nature and combined forest management systems (<ce:cross-ref refid="f0010" id="c0385">Fig. 2</ce:cross-ref>). In Pennataro, the TreMs occurrence was 0.28 for no management and 0.27 for close-to-nature and combined with a DBH class of 15 cm, while it increases to 0.93 and 0.92 for a DBH class of 45 cm. The sensitivity analysis showed the same trend for all considered forest management systems. Differences are relevant between no management and combined and close-to-nature forestry: higher TreMs occurrence for smaller sizes and lower TreMs occurrence for larger sizes (<ce:cross-ref refid="f0010" id="c0390">Fig. 2</ce:cross-ref>).</ce:para>
                     <ce:para id="p0140" view="all">In the case of TreMs richness, the sensitivity analysis showed differences among the three investigated sites (<ce:cross-ref refid="f0010" id="c0395">Fig. 2</ce:cross-ref>). The trend in H-dependent variation of TreMs richness in Giffone was different compared to those in Pennataro and Campaegli, showing a little reduction for H &gt; 30 m. Overall, the richness was higher in Pennataro than in Giffone and Campaegli reaching 7, 3.5 and 2.5 respectively. On average, TreMs richness was very low (&lt;1) for trees with H &lt; 15 m, particularly in Campaegli and Giffone. In Pennataro, it increased significantly for trees with H &gt; 15 m, reaching the absolute highest values with values of tree H ranging between 18 m and 25 m, even if on the average it continued to increase (<ce:cross-ref refid="f0010" id="c0400">Fig. 2</ce:cross-ref>). Differently, in Campaegli and Giffone the absolute highest richness corresponded to H values ranging between 20 m and 30 m. In Campaegli, the increase in H corresponded to an average increase in TreMs richness, while in Giffone, it showed an opposite trend.</ce:para>
                     <ce:para id="p0145" view="all">The sensitivity analysis highlighted that close-to-nature management system resulted in the highest TreMs richness in all sites, while no management the lowest. In Pennataro, the close-to-nature forestry allowed for an average increase of 6% in TreMs richness, achieving 22% for values of H ranging between 15 m and 20 m, and of 19% with H between 25 m and 30 m. Through the combined management system, there was an increase of 3.5% of TreMs richness compared to no management, with values of 16% and 9% for H of 15–20 m and 25–30 m. In Campaegli, TreMs richness increased on average of about 4% and 2% when passing from the no management to the close-to-nature and combined management systems, respectively. The differences in TreMs richness were more pronounced for H values ranging between 20 and 25 m and 25–30 m in close-to-nature, and between 30 and 35 m considering the combined management system. In Giffone, the average increase of TreMs richness was about 13% considering close-to-nature, and 2% considering combined management system. More in detail, the average richness value for combined management system further increased (reaching 8%) excluding the H values &gt; 35 m, for which a 22% of decrease was reported. However, the higher increases were found for H values ranging between 15 m and 20 m, with an increase of 57% and 29% for close-to-nature and combined management systems, respectively. For taller trees in Giffone (H &gt; 30 m), no management fostered the development of more TreMs types compared to the other management systems, even if richness decreased. Further details about the relationships between the occurrence and richness of TreMs and structural parameters are reported in supplementary material (Annex 4).</ce:para>
                  </ce:section>
               </ce:section>
               <ce:section id="s0050" view="all">
                  <ce:label>4</ce:label>
                  <ce:section-title id="st065">Discussion</ce:section-title>
                  <ce:section id="s0055" view="all">
                     <ce:label>4.1</ce:label>
                     <ce:section-title id="st070">Microhabitats depend on tree characteristics</ce:section-title>
                     <ce:para id="p0150" view="all">Despite some studies only recently focused on TreMs in Mediterranean forests (<ce:cross-ref refid="b0200" id="c0405">Marziliano et al., 2021</ce:cross-ref>), the present study is the first exploring the relationship between the most relevant tree structural parameters and the occurrence and richness of TreMs at the tree level in this geographic area. Our models were built on 1416 living trees from three different Mediterranean forests with different forest structures and management systems.</ce:para>
                     <ce:para id="p0155" view="all">Results demonstrate that there is a close relationship between tree structural parameters (e.g. large trees) and the occurrence and richness of TreMs, as also observed in other forest ecosystems (<ce:cross-refs refid="b0020 b0235" id="r0080">Asbeck et al., 2019; Paillet et al., 2019</ce:cross-refs>). Overall, identifying such characteristics strongly supports forest management practices such as e.g. tree marking and selection of habitat trees to be retained, thus supporting the integrative forest management approach (<ce:cross-ref refid="b0230" id="c0410">Paillet et al., 2018</ce:cross-ref>).</ce:para>
                     <ce:para id="p0160" view="all">Though DBH remains one of the most impacting forest structural parameters on TreMs occurrence, we highlight that additional tree characteristics might play a significant role, such as for example the slenderness coefficient. Despite most of TreM-trees have a DBH &gt; 25 cm, TreMs, such as <ce:italic>small size trunk rot hole</ce:italic> (CV31), <ce:italic>dendrothelms</ce:italic> (CV41), <ce:italic>root buttress concavities</ce:italic> (GR11 and GR13), <ce:italic>lianas</ce:italic> (EP33) and <ce:italic>crown microsoil</ce:italic> (OT21) can occur on smaller tree sizes. TreMs as <ce:italic>sap run</ce:italic> (OT11), <ce:italic>epiphytic bryophytes</ce:italic> (EP31), <ce:italic>medium-size trunk rot hole</ce:italic> (CV32) and <ce:italic>hollow branch</ce:italic> (CV33) often occur on trees with higher values of DBH. A more complex variable combination resulted of significant importance for TreMs richness: basal area, tree volume, tree height, live-to-crown ratio and slenderness coefficient (see <ce:cross-ref refid="t0030" id="c0415">Table 6</ce:cross-ref>). Despite the positive relationship between tree height and TreMs richness, our results surprisingly reveal that taller trees are not associated with increased TreMs richness (see <ce:cross-ref refid="f0010" id="c0420">Fig. 2</ce:cross-ref>). Since the dominant tree height is an useful indicator of stand productivity (<ce:cross-ref refid="b0250" id="c0425">Pretzsch, 2010</ce:cross-ref>), we argue that forest stands with intermediate productivity values are likely more prone to bearing TreMs than highly productive stands. However, this aspect still remains underexplored, despite it was demonstrated that tree vitality has implications for the occurrence and richness of TreMs (<ce:cross-refs refid="b0110 b0335" id="r0085">Großmann et al., 2018; Winter et al., 2015</ce:cross-refs>). In addition, observing TreMs on the crown and tree top of tall trees is challenging and subject to surveying errors.</ce:para>
                     <ce:para id="p0165" view="all">The slenderness coefficient shows a significant negative relationship with both occurrence and richness of TreMs, particularly for values lower than 90 (see Annex 4 in supplementary material). This is rather obvious especially considering that SL might be affected by the combination of DBH and H, i.e. higher DBH, lower SL. Most of the studies on TreMs indeed only focused on DBH, probably because DBH is easier to measure in the field as well as it is the most commonly measured parameter in national forest inventories. Our findings demonstrate that higher is the individual tree stability (i.e. lower H to DBH ratio), higher are TreMs occurrence and richness. We therefore argue that forest management practices such as e.g., diversification of forest structures with retention of larger than taller trees (in small patches) are likely beneficial to both increasing biodiversity values (through microhabitats) (e.g. <ce:cross-ref refid="b0115" id="c0430">Gustafsson et al., 2012</ce:cross-ref>) and ensuring tree resistance to climate-induced disturbances (e.g. wind throw; (<ce:cross-ref refid="b0295" id="c0435">Skrzyszewski and Pach, 2020</ce:cross-ref>)).</ce:para>
                     <ce:para id="p0170" view="all">The random effect implemented in this study allowed to obtain a better performance of the models, highlighting that the impact of tree species is higher for TreMs occurrence (SD = ±0.52), and lower for TreMs richness (SD = ±0.31). Overall, we can confirm that tree structural parameters are more impacting than tree species, especially for TreMs richness. However, the effect of tree species on TreMs occurrence is higher than the magnitude of both crown projection area, and slenderness coefficient, but lower than the magnitude of DBH. Promoting the mixture of tree species through forest management can increase not only the occurrence, but indirectly also the richness of TreMs (<ce:cross-refs refid="b0160 b0235 b0330" id="r0090">Larrieu and Cabanettes, 2012; Paillet et al., 2019; Vuidot et al., 2011</ce:cross-refs>).</ce:para>
                  </ce:section>
                  <ce:section id="s0060" view="all">
                     <ce:label>4.2</ce:label>
                     <ce:section-title id="st075">Tree-related microhabitat occurrence and richness vary by management system</ce:section-title>
                     <ce:para id="p0175" view="all">Results from sensitivity analysis confirm that forest management interacts with occurrence and richness of microhabitats (<ce:cross-refs refid="b0020 b0025" id="r0095">Asbeck et al., 2019; Augustynczik et al., 2019</ce:cross-refs>). We demonstrate that the hypothetical modification of stand structure when varying management intensity results in diverse responses from microhabitats (see <ce:cross-ref refid="f0010" id="c0440">Fig. 2</ce:cross-ref>). This divergence could be more visible if two forest management systems differing in frequency and intensity of interventions (e.g. thinning) were considered. We found that combined objective forestry originates higher TreMs occurrence compared to no management or passive management at least in the short time period (cf. <ce:cross-ref refid="b0140" id="c0445">Kozák et al., 2018</ce:cross-ref>). However, differences among management scenarios are not visibly pronounced, especially at early developmental stages (i.e. DBH, <ce:cross-ref refid="f0010" id="c0450">Fig. 2</ce:cross-ref>). Therefore, we might argue that increasing the management intensity as foreseen in combined objective forestry – mostly combining ordinary thinning and final cutting regimes with prolonged rotation lengths, would promote the retention of larger trees (including TreM-trees, or better habitat trees) on site, and likely originate higher microhabitats’ availability. Similarly, if closer-to-nature forestry practices were implemented, the frequency of selective thinning as well as the potential retention of deadwood on site would help increase the occurrence of microhabitats (<ce:cross-ref refid="b0230" id="c0455">Paillet et al., 2018</ce:cross-ref>). This aspect also supports our findings highlighting that after a certain dimensional threshold (50 cm &lt; DBH &lt; 70 cm; see <ce:cross-ref refid="f0010" id="c0460">Fig. 2</ce:cross-ref>), an overall improvement of TreMs occurrence was expected, while for larger DBH, the combined management system foster the increase of TreMs occurrence.</ce:para>
                     <ce:para id="p0180" view="all">As also highlighted by <ce:cross-ref refid="b0010" id="c0465">Asbeck et al. (2021)</ce:cross-ref>, the relationship between TreMs richness and management practices is difficult to scrutinize, and largely depends on the scale of management implementation as well as on the time since the last forestry intervention. The sensitivity analysis indeed highlights that for older stands as in Giffone, the absence of management interventions (i.e. no management) could facilitate the development of more TreMs types. Differently, in Pennataro and Campaegli, where the tree sizes are smaller, the close to nature and the combined management systems provide slightly more types of TreMs. We therefore deduce that more complex forest structures (with a reduced number of dominant trees) likely referring to uneven-aged, unmanaged stands (or at least stands without management interventions for a long time) can have more TreMs richness than even-aged, recently managed stands (see e.g. in Italy; <ce:cross-ref refid="b0200" id="c0470">Marziliano et al., 2021</ce:cross-ref>). On the other hand, the retention of large trees which are left on site over their commercial maturity are extremely important to ensure the conservation of biodiversity over time, also through maintaining abundance and richness of microhabitats in actively managed stands (e.g. <ce:cross-ref refid="b0120" id="c0475">Gustafsson et al., 2020</ce:cross-ref>).</ce:para>
                  </ce:section>
                  <ce:section id="s0065" view="all">
                     <ce:label>4.3</ce:label>
                     <ce:section-title id="st080">Limitations of the study and future perspectives for practical forest management</ce:section-title>
                     <ce:para id="p0185" view="all">We assessed the relationship between structural characteristics by management system and richness and occurrence of TreMs at tree level rather than at stand level. This is because the occurrence of TreMs and the probability that a TreM forms on a tree directly depend on individual tree characteristics (<ce:cross-refs refid="b0075 b0170" id="r0100">Courbaud et al., 2017; Larrieu et al., 2017</ce:cross-refs>) and only indirectly on the applied forest management regime at the stand level.</ce:para>
                     <ce:para id="p0190" view="all">As in other studies dealing with the prediction of TreMs occurrence and richness (<ce:cross-refs refid="b0020 b0110 b0235" id="r0105">Asbeck et al., 2019; Großmann et al., 2018; Paillet et al., 2019</ce:cross-refs>), the definition of a dimensional threshold for the occurrence of TreMs remains challenging. Based on our findings, the mean DBH is higher in the TreM-trees compared to the non-TreM-trees. We therefore confirm that the occurrence and richness of TreMs increase significantly for trees with DBH &gt; 20 cm. We also point out that taller trees (i.e. H &gt; 25 m) are not associated with more TreMs, while trees with lower slenderness coefficient are more prone to bear TreMs (see also <ce:cross-ref refid="b0010" id="c0480">Asbeck et al., 2021</ce:cross-ref>).</ce:para>
                     <ce:para id="p0195" view="all">We consider our results rather accurate (see <ce:cross-ref refid="t0020" id="c0485">Table 4</ce:cross-ref>). However, there is still about 15–20% of variability that is not explained by our models. We therefore suggest that enlarging the dataset (e.g. surveyed trees), covering a larger DBH range, and exploring different forest types could further improve the model accuracy. We obtained a good modelling performance with a reduced number of parameters. However, the consideration of other environmental parameters such as e.g. terrain, aspect, slope and micro-climatic variables could likely improve the model robustness (<ce:cross-refs refid="b0015 b0235" id="r0110">Asbeck et al., 2020b; Paillet et al., 2019</ce:cross-refs>). Further improvement on the TreMs detecting could be reached considering the deadwood amount and its decay stage (<ce:cross-ref refid="b0155" id="c0490">Larrieu et al., 2014</ce:cross-ref>). It is well known that deadwood is an important indicator of forest biodiversity (<ce:cross-ref refid="b0240" id="c0495">Parisi et al., 2016</ce:cross-ref>) especially in unmanaged stands. However, identifying a minimum threshold for deadwood amount, even under economically-viable management conditions, is very challenging, but also necessary to better implement the integrative forest management approach. Similarly, data about the frequency by TreMs type rather than the simple occurrence (presence/absence) could further contribute to increase the accuracy of the model.</ce:para>
                     <ce:para id="p0200" view="all">The sensitivity analysis in this study is based on average changes of structural parameters of the stands depending on broad categories of forest management systems. More site-specific results on the relationship between forest management and TreMs occurrence and richness could be obtained if harvesting activities were concretely carried out on-site or virtually simulated (e.g. <ce:cross-ref refid="b0270" id="c0500">Santopuoli et al., 2019</ce:cross-ref>). Moreover, the use of average stand characteristics resulting from broad definition of management systems could hide a deeper understanding of peculiar effects from practices such as e.g. retention activities, on larger trees, deadwood, etc., and subsequently on microhabitats’ occurrence and richness.</ce:para>
                     <ce:para id="p0205" view="all">Finally, we did not consider to what extent the time since the last forest interventions could have affected TreMs occurrence and richness, as instead recently explored in unmanaged forests by <ce:cross-ref refid="b0200" id="c0505">Marziliano et al. (2021)</ce:cross-ref>. We primarily focussed on assessing the relationship between current forest structures and TreMs richness and occurrence. We secondarily used forest management alternatives to vary the current forest structures towards those hypotheticals. Of course, the time elapse since the last human intervention could have played a role in determining current forest structures in our sites. However, based on the main findings, we might conclude that time since the last human intervention has a secondary role for TreMs richness and occurrence if compared to structural parameters and tree species (see e.g. absence of harvesting activity in Pennataro).</ce:para>
                     <ce:para id="p0210" view="all">In order to preserve biodiversity through microhabitats, forest management of productive forests should be oriented to identifying and maintaining large trees on site and focused on reducing the competition among close individuals for fostering the crown expansion (see also the integrative approach in forest management <ce:cross-ref refid="b0055" id="c0510">Boncina (2011)</ce:cross-ref>). Furthermore, a homogeneous distribution of habitat trees in the forest will ensure biodiversity conservation balancing the trade-offs with other forest ecosystem services. Nevertheless, calculating a suitable number of habitat trees to be retained would deserve further exploration (<ce:cross-ref refid="b0015" id="c0515">Asbeck et al., 2020b</ce:cross-ref>). There is indeed the need of assessing spatial dispersion and/or minimum distance among habitat trees to promote biodiversity conservation (see e.g. spatial patterns of TreM-tree (<ce:cross-ref refid="b0195" id="c0520">Martin et al., 2021</ce:cross-ref>). Moreover, it is important to define a reliable method for assessing the habitat value of trees, discriminating between trees with high TreMs occurrence and those with high TreMs richness, fostering the recognition and the selection of habitat trees, promoting biodiversity conservation.</ce:para>
                  </ce:section>
               </ce:section>
               <ce:section id="s0070" view="all">
                  <ce:label>5</ce:label>
                  <ce:section-title id="st085">Conclusions</ce:section-title>
                  <ce:para id="p0215" view="all">Our study provides a novel contribution to the assessment of occurrence and richness of microhabitats, in relation with a large set of forest structural parameters and in combination with alternative forest management regimes. The present study also contributes to an overall understanding of forest microhabitats in the Mediterranean context. We find that large trees are more prone to bear TreMs and to be considered as potential habitat trees. Further investigations are necessary to correctly classify habitat trees based on the habitat value of TreMs. On the contrary, the richness of TreMs increases with medium size of tree height. This study highlights that DBH, slenderness coefficient, volume, basal area and tree height are the most impacting forest structural parameters for assessing TreMs richness and occurrence. Tree species affects TreMs occurrence and indirectly also TreMs richness due to the highest forest structural complexity of mixed forests.</ce:para>
                  <ce:para id="p0220" view="all">The use of TreMs as proxies for the conservation status of forest biodiversity is gaining an increasing attention, even if a whole understanding of TreMs occurrence and richness in relation to forest structures, tree species and management deserves further research. Knowing the existing relationship between forest structural parameters and TreMs occurrence and richness strongly supports the implementation of integrative forest management approach balancing biodiversity conservation with the provision of other forest ecosystem goods and services. Assessing the evolution of tree growth and TreMs development remains a challenge, but it represents an interesting aspect to investigate. Moreover, from a scientific point of view, understanding how tree characteristics (e.g., phenology, trunk morphology) interact with TreMs still remains challenging. Further efforts are still necessary to assess the interrelationships between TreMs and individual tree species.</ce:para>
                  <ce:para id="p0225" view="all">The present study highlights that introducing management (e.g. passing from no management to combined objective forestry) in our forests would promote higher occurrence of tree-related microhabitats. Nevertheless, we also show that forest management intensity plays a less relevant role in tree microhabitats’ occurrence and richness than individual tree characteristics, especially at local scale. Time since last forestry intervention determining the evolution of forest structures (e.g. tree size, deadwood amount) might be an interesting aspect to explore in future research to deeper analyse the anthropogenic effects on microhabitats. Forest management therefore needs to be tailored to specific stands characteristics and diversified at landscape level through balancing production with conservation goals. Only through integrating biodiversity conservation issues within ordinary management, the sustainability of human impact on forests can be improved.</ce:para>
               </ce:section>
               <ce:section id="s0075" view="all">
                  <ce:section-title id="st090">CRediT authorship contribution statement</ce:section-title>
                  <ce:para id="p0230" view="all">
                     <ce:bold>Giovanni Santopuoli:</ce:bold> Conceptualization, Methodology, Investigation, Writing – original draft, Writing – review &amp; editing. <ce:bold>Matteo Vizzarri:</ce:bold> Methodology, Investigation, Writing – review &amp; editing. <ce:bold>Pierdomenico Spina:</ce:bold> Data curation, Methodology, Software, Formal analysis. <ce:bold>Mauro Maesano:</ce:bold> Visualization, Investigation. <ce:bold>Giuseppe Scarascia Mugnozza:</ce:bold> Supervision, Funding acquisition. <ce:bold>Bruno Lasserre:</ce:bold> Supervision, Project administration.</ce:para>
               </ce:section>
            </ce:sections>
            <ce:conflict-of-interest id="coi005" view="all">
               <ce:section-title id="st095">Declaration of Competing Interest</ce:section-title>
               <ce:para id="p0235" view="all">The authors declare that they have no known competing financial interests or personal relationships that could have appeared to influence the work reported in this paper.</ce:para>
            </ce:conflict-of-interest>
            <ce:acknowledgment id="ak005" view="all">
               <ce:section role="contributing" id="s0080" view="all">
                  <ce:section-title id="st100">Acknowledgements</ce:section-title>
                  <ce:para id="p0240" view="all">This work was realized with the contribution of the PRIN 2015YW8JWA_004 “<ce:italic>La filiera corta nel settore biomasse-legno: approvvigionamento, tracciabilità, certificazione e sequestro di Carbonio. Innovazioni per la bioedilizia e l'efficienza energetica</ce:italic>”. We thank dr. Mirko Di Febbraro and dr. Carlotta Ferrara for reviewing the statistical approach, and dr. Marco di Cristofaro, Renato Zompanti and dr. Federico Moresi for their support in the collection of field data. We also thank Marco Lelli for his support during the field surveys phase.</ce:para>
               </ce:section>
               <ce:section id="s0085" view="all">
                  <ce:section-title id="st105">Disclaimer</ce:section-title>
                  <ce:para id="p0245" view="all">The views expressed are purely those of the writers and may not in any circumstances be regarded as stating an official position of the European Commission or any other Government Agency.</ce:para>
                  <ce:para id="p0250" view="all">This research did not receive any specific grant from funding agencies in the public, commercial, or not-for-profit sectors.</ce:para>
               </ce:section>
            </ce:acknowledgment>
